Out of curiosity do you have the cache enabled on the broker? It would make it need to do merges of results for every segment which doesn't scale super well. I would think this merging resources situation could be annoying even without that, but that would definitely make it worse.

Fwiw, I wouldn't call it "improper" since this is how it is designed (merges happen in http threads even on historicals -- the processing threads are really only used for per-segment stuff). But it does sound like we can do better.

> 1) using the processing executor service with properly set query priority runnables. This has a risk of deadlock if not handled correctly, where all threads are taken up by merge needs without the ability for worker sub-tasks to do their thing.

This seems like the best way to approach it, but we have to be careful to chunk up the work into small enough chunks so a big merge doesn't starve out the processing pool.

Is it possible this is due to another one of these possible reasons?

- The `druid.server.http.numThreads` limit has been reached on the historicals. In this case, `query/time` would be smaller than `query/node/time`, since `query/time` measures from when an http thread picks up the query. But a query could spend substantial time waiting for an http thread to pick it up.
- The `druid.broker.http.numConnections` limit has been reached on the broker. Same deal, but the concurrency limit is client-side rather than server-side.

A good test case for this would be a SQL query like:

```
select floor(__time to day), count(*) from foo group by 1 limit 2
```

Which should plan into a timeseries query with a `limit: 2` parameter. But today, it plans into, I think, a topN.

I could see a few ways to solve this:

1. Formally define that topN and groupBy behave differently. But this is unappealing, since I think you'd want topN and groupBys that "look equivalent" to behave similarly.
2. Modify topN to behave like groupBy. However, this is unappealing too, since I like how topN works now.
3. Modify groupBy to behave like topN when grouping on one dimension. Extend this to grouping on more than one dimensions by making groupBy "implode" rows when _any_ multi-value dimension in the grouping set is empty. So if any of them is empty, the result row disappears. This is pretty consistent with how grouping would behave if you think of the multi-value dimensions as like an inner join on some kind of virtual table. It may be surprising to users, though, that their rows go "missing".
4. Modify groupBy to behave like topN when grouping on one dimension. Extend this to grouping on more than one dimensions by making groupBy treat empty multi-value dimensions as nulls in this case. This has an advantage over (3) in that rows never go "missing", but it's a little less internally consistent.
